          "body": "Verse 13 closes the chapter with one of Revelation's most haunting images: a solitary eagle flying *in mid-heaven*, crying *woe, woe, woe* to the earth-dwellers. *Aetos* can be eagle or vulture (cf. Matt 24:28); some commentators (G. K. Beale, *NIGTC*) note the carrion-bird overtones. The threefold *woe* corresponds exactly to the three remaining trumpets (9:12; 11:14). The eagle's announcement is *severe mercy* — God warns before He completes. *Those who dwell on the earth* (*katoikountes epi tēs gēs*) is a Revelation technical phrase (3:10; 6:10; 11:10; 13:8; 17:8) for the world-system that has refused the Lamb. They are warned, but the chapter offers no indication they will repent — chapter 9 will explicitly say they did not (9:20-21)."
